        <td bgcolor="dimgray" colspan="2" ><img src="icon_posticon.gif" border="0" hspace="3"><font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="1">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/20/2001&nbsp;:&nbsp; 13:34:37</font>
        
		&nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=737"><img src="icon_profile.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Show Profile" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>
        
			&nbsp;<a href="JavaScript:openWindow('pop_mail.asp?id=737')"><img src="icon_email.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Email Poster" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>

        &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=71694&TOPIC_ID=8870&FORUM_ID=1&CAT_ID=1&Forum_Title=General+Discussions&Topic_Title=Smart+Resistances%3F&M="><img src="icon_reply_topic.gif" height=15 width=15 alt="Reply with Quote" border="0" align="absmiddle" hspace="6"></a>


        <hr noshade size="1">
        
        <font color="white" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2">A question about this same thing came up once while some friends of mine and I were playing AD-n-D  many years ago.  (2nd edition)  And we found an answer for it in the rule book, which basically stated that in order to cast a 'friendly' spell on someone, they are voluntarily lowering their resistances, which they can do at will.</P><P>While that may not seem like that big of a deal, the thing was, in our campaign, we played by the premise that you could not innately tell anything about someone, other than what you could see (or could magically detect, etc.)  This made for some very interesting games, because I played a Necromancer way back then too ;)</P><P>We were playing our characters as realistically as possible, with all the little nuances that real people have.  For the most part, regardless of the race/class/alignment, we worked excellently together as a team, despite the wide variety in our group.  However, every once in a while someone would be holding a grudge against someone for some petty thing or another, and when it came time to cast a benefitial spell on them...   well, it definately added a level of excitement to the game that wasn't present before.  It is truely the way role-playing games were meant to be played.</P><P><IMG src="http://neverquest.homestead.com/files/OurMoon/OurMoon.jpg"><BR><i>"Verant celebrates the success of their latest expansion."<i></P><P> <a href="#top"><img src="icon_go_up.gif" height=15 width=15 border="0" align="right" alt="Go to Top of Page"></a></font></td>
      </tr>

